title Neth deterministic simulation lap 1 lands GREEN; the whole ladder closes
prompt Keaton wrote "kg best way yes" -- keep-going, in the best judged way, approving the deterministic-simulation horizon this time (the item deliberately deferred two turns ago as deserving its own dedicated pass).
think read the horizon's own naming in TASKS.md and pattern 4 of the IronBeetle-patterns study together before scoping anything: seeded fault/delay injection over the replica set, named "built after the real replica laps" -- which the prior two sessions' own root-install and apply-step laps now satisfy.
think scoped the lap honestly rather than reaching for a full network simulator: Neth's own load-bearing claim is that record ORDER in the log is fixed and folds deterministically (already proven by the root witness and the two-posture install); what a real network actually varies is not that order but WHEN each record reaches a replica. So this lap seeds exactly the delivery timing -- a per-record, seeded drop-then-retry schedule -- rather than reinventing the ordering claim a second time.
think designed neth_sim.rye's bound (max_ticks_per_record, LivenessFailure) before writing the witness, since a fault-injection harness that could loop forever on an adversarial seed would be a real hazard rather than a proof -- the same discipline neth_serial_core.rye's own max_append_bytes bound already modeled for a different kind of limit.
think built and ran the witness directly on this cloud sandbox and caught a genuine weakness in the first draft before committing: claim 2 (different seed, different schedule, same root) used seed 0x5eed0002, which happened to produce the SAME trace as seed 0x5eed0001 by coincidence -- true, yet not a convincing demonstration of "genuinely different." Wrote a small throwaway probe program (not committed) sweeping 32 seeds to find one that visibly diverges (0x5eed0004, trace {1,5,3} against {2,1,1}), then used that seed instead. This is exactly the kind of thing running witnesses in the same sitting they are written catches, that a host-run handoff would not have surfaced until later.
think verified the claim that faults change timing, never the outcome, by asserting the zero-fault baseline (drop_pct 0) converges on the identical root every faulted run converged on -- proving convergence rather than merely asserting it by construction.
think ran all six Neth/Mantra witnesses landed across this whole thread together at the end (root witness, serial core, root install, apply step, Mantra's own apply step, this simulation lap) to confirm nothing regressed -- all six real GREEN in one pass.
obs this closes every named lap and horizon in the Neth build ladder from external-research/20260714-041542_ironbeetle-patterns-for-the-neth-ladder.md -- named plainly in TASKS.md rather than left implicit, since a closed ladder is worth noticing as its own real milestone, not just another checked box.
obs the deferred-then-approved shape held exactly as reasoned two turns ago: this lap genuinely benefited from its own dedicated pass (the seed-selection probe, the honest scoping decision about what varies and what does not) rather than riding along with a mechanical sibling lap.
